<reading-questions><title> Check your Understanding </title>
	
	<exercise label="p2-c1-s1-i1"><title> <em>We can solve <m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x^3 - 7</m> for <m>y</m> by differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m></em> </title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				<em>We can solve <m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x^3 - 7</m> for <m>y</m> by differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</em>
			</p>
		</statement>
		<choices>
			<choice>
				<statement> True </statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Incorrect, we integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement>False</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Correct!
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
		</choices>
	</exercise>

	<exercise label="p2-c1-s1-i2"><title> <em>The equation <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = \ln(3x+1)</m> implies that the solution, <m>y</m>, is the antiderivative of <m>\ln(3x+1)</m></em> </title>
		<statement>
			<em>The equation <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = \ln(3x+1)</m> implies that the solution, <m>y</m>, is the antiderivative of <m>\ln(3x+1)</m>.</em>
		</statement>
		<choices>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement> True </statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Correct, integrating both sides gives 
						<me>
							y = \int \ln(3x+1)\ dx \quad \leftarrow \text{anti-derivative of } \ln(3x+1)
						</me>.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice>
				<statement>False</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Incorrect.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</choice>
		</choices>

	</exercise>

